(43, 4, 28, 40, 28, 8, 8, NULL, 'Joyful Announcement of Good News', 'This connection highlights the theme of urgency in sharing transformative news. Both passages depict individuals who, after significant encounters, quickly go to tell others about what they have experienced.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 28, 41, 16, 8, 10, NULL, 'Women as Messengers', 'This connection highlights the role of women in proclaiming significant news. In both passages, women leave their initial tasks to share important messages with others.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 28, 42, 24, 9, 9, 'went her way into the city', 'Witnessing and Proclamation', 'This connection highlights the theme of individuals sharing significant news. Both passages depict a person leaving to tell others about an important revelation.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 29, 66, 22, 17, 17, 'Come, see a man', 'Invitation to Encounter Christ', 'This connection highlights the invitation to come and see Jesus as the Christ in John 4:29, and the call to come and take the water of life in Revelation 22:17. Both passages emphasize the accessibility of Christ and the life He offers.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 29, 46, 14, 24, 25, 'told me all things that ever I did', 'Revelation of Secrets', 'This connection highlights the theme of revealing personal truths. In both passages, individuals experience the unveiling of their inner secrets, leading to a recognition of divine presence.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 29, 43, 1, 41, 49, NULL, 'Recognition of the Christ', 'Both passages emphasize the discovery of Jesus as the Christ. In John 4:29, the woman invites others to see Jesus, while in John 1:41-49, Philip and Nathanael also invite others to come and see Jesus as the Messiah.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 29, 43, 4, 25, 25, NULL, 'Recognition of the Messiah', 'Both passages emphasize the woman''s understanding of the Messiah''s role in revealing truth. In John 4:25, she anticipates that the Messiah will tell them all things, which she later confirms in John 4:29 when she identifies Jesus as the Christ who has done just that.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 29, 40, 12, 23, 23, 'is not this the Christ?', 'Recognition of Christ''s Identity', 'This connection highlights the recognition of Jesus as the Messiah. Both passages feature people questioning if Jesus is the awaited figure, with one asking if He is ''the Christ'' and the other if He is ''the son of David.''', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 30, 23, 60, 8, 8, 'came unto him', 'Gathering of People Imagery', 'This connection highlights the imagery of people coming together. In John 4:30, the people come out of the city, while Isaiah 60:8 describes people flying like doves to their windows, suggesting a gathering or movement towards a central figure.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 30, 40, 2, 1, 3, 'came unto him', 'Journey to Worship the King', 'This connection highlights the theme of individuals coming to Jesus to seek him. In both passages, there is a movement towards Jesus, whether from the city or from the east, emphasizing the recognition of his significance as the King.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 30, 40, 8, 11, 12, 'came unto him', 'Invitation to the Kingdom', 'This connection highlights the theme of inclusion in the kingdom of heaven. In John 4:30, the people come to Jesus, paralleling Matthew 8:11-12, where many from outside Israel are invited to sit with the patriarchs.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 30, 42, 17, 16, 18, 'came unto him', 'Gratitude and Samaritan Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of returning to Jesus, as seen in both passages. In John 4:30, people come to Jesus, while in Luke 17:16-18, a Samaritan returns to give thanks, emphasizing the importance of gratitude.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 30, 44, 8, 5, 8, 'came unto him', 'Connection of Outreach and Response', 'This connection highlights the movement of people towards Christ. In both passages, individuals leave their locations to seek Jesus, resulting in significant spiritual engagement and transformation.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 30, 44, 10, 33, 33, 'came unto him', 'Gathering to Hear God''s Message', 'This connection highlights the theme of people coming together to receive divine instruction. In both passages, individuals leave their locations to gather before Jesus and Peter, respectively, to hear what God has commanded.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 30, 45, 5, 20, 20, 'came unto him', 'Connection of Grace and Response', 'This connection highlights the movement towards Jesus in John 4:30, paralleling the abundance of grace in Romans 5:20. Both passages emphasize a response to a greater reality, whether it be the people coming to Jesus or grace overcoming sin.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 31, 1, 24, 33, 33, 'eat', 'Focus on Purpose Before Eating', 'This connection highlights the priority of purpose over physical needs in both passages. In John, the disciples urge Jesus to eat, while in Genesis, the servant refuses to eat until he fulfills his mission.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 31, 43, 1, 38, 38, 'Master', 'Connection of Master and Rabbi', 'Both passages emphasize the title ''Master'' as a form of respect for Jesus. In John 4:31, the disciples address Him as ''Master,'' while in John 1:38, the followers refer to Him as ''Rabbi,'' which is interpreted as ''Master.'' This connection highlights the recognition of Jesus'' authority.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 31, 40, 23, 7, 7, 'Master', 'Disciples'' Respect for Authority', 'This connection highlights the disciples'' recognition of Jesus'' authority, as they address him with respect, similar to how people call others ''Rabbi'' in Matthew. Both passages emphasize the importance of titles and roles in the context of teaching and leadership.', 'theme', 0.3, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 31, 44, 16, 30, 34, NULL, 'Theme of Hospitality and Nourishment', 'Both passages emphasize the act of providing food and care for others. In John 4:31, the disciples urge Jesus to eat, while in Acts 16:34, the jailer sets meat before Paul and Silas, highlighting the importance of hospitality in the early Christian community.', 'theme', 0.3, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 32, 18, 23, 12, 12, 'meat to eat that ye know not of', 'Connection of Spiritual Sustenance', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of spiritual nourishment over physical food. In John, Jesus speaks of ''meat to eat'' that is unknown to his disciples, while Job values ''the words of his mouth'' more than necessary food.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 32, 19, 119, 103, 103, 'meat to eat that ye know not of', 'Spiritual Nourishment and Sweetness', 'This connection highlights the theme of nourishment found in both passages. In John 4:32, Jesus speaks of spiritual sustenance, while Psalms 119:103 describes the sweetness of God''s words, suggesting that both emphasize the importance of spiritual food.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 32, 43, 4, 34, 34, 'meat to eat that ye know not of', 'Connection of Spiritual Nourishment', 'This connection highlights the concept of ''meat'' as a metaphor for spiritual sustenance. Both passages emphasize the importance of fulfilling divine purpose over physical needs.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 32, 20, 18, 20, 20, NULL, 'Connection of Spiritual Nourishment', 'This connection highlights the idea of satisfaction derived from different sources. In John 4:32, Jesus speaks of a nourishment beyond physical food, while Proverbs 18:20 emphasizes satisfaction from the words one speaks.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 32, 24, 15, 16, 16, 'meat to eat that ye know not of', 'Connection of Spiritual Nourishment', 'This connection highlights the theme of spiritual sustenance found in both passages. In John 4:32, Jesus refers to a ''meat'' unknown to his disciples, paralleling Jeremiah 15:16 where the prophet speaks of ''eating'' God''s words as a source of joy.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 32, 19, 63, 5, 5, 'I have meat to eat', 'Satisfaction and Spiritual Nourishment', 'Both passages emphasize a deep sense of satisfaction. John 4:32 speaks of spiritual nourishment, while Psalms 63:5 describes satisfaction akin to physical sustenance.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 32, 20, 14, 10, 10, NULL, 'Understanding Inner Experiences', 'This connection highlights the theme of inner experiences. Both passages emphasize the personal nature of understanding one''s own feelings, whether it be the unknown sustenance in John or the heart''s bitterness in Proverbs.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 33, 40, 16, 6, 11, 'Hath any man brought him ought to eat?', 'Disciples'' Misunderstanding of Bread', 'This connection highlights the disciples'' confusion regarding bread in both passages. In John 4:33, they question if anyone has brought Jesus food, while in Matthew 16:6-11, they misunderstand Jesus'' warning about leaven as a reference to their lack of bread.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
